excerpt: Natural attraction where dark- & sandy-colored rivers meet & parallel each other without mixing.
detail_description: The Meeting of Waters, locally known as Encuetro de los Aguas, is a must-see natural attraction near Manaus. Here, the dark Rio Negro and the milky Rio Solimoes come together to form the Amazon River. The distinct colors of these rivers run alongside each other for nearly a mile without mixing due to differences in temperature, density, and velocity. This phenomenon creates a stunning spectacle that attracts many travelers.
name: Meeting of Waters
address: Careiro da Várzea - State of Amazonas, 69255-000, Brazil

excerpt: Famed Renaissance theater built in 1896 during the city's rubber boom & hosting concerts & tours.
detail_description: The Amazon Theatre, a renowned Renaissance theater constructed during Manaus's rubber boom in 1896, is a stunning landmark influenced by European design and materials. The opulent venue hosts various events, including an opera festival in April and May. Visitors can take guided tours to admire the theater's grand construction. Situated at Largo de Sao Sebastiao, it is surrounded by attractions like the central church and a lively square for a complete experience of Manaus's charm.
name: Teatro Amazonas
address: Largo de São Sebastião - Centro, Manaus - AM, 69067-080, Brazil

detail_description: When exploring Manaus, a visit to the Mercado Municipal Adolpho Lisboa is an absolute must. This vibrant market, inspired by the original Les Halles in Paris, serves as a lively gathering spot for both locals and tourists. Here, you can indulge in unique Amazonian delicacies while browsing through an array of fresh produce, exotic meats, fish, tropical fruits, and colorful handicrafts that make perfect souvenirs.
name: Mercado Municipal Adolpho Lisboa
address: R. dos Barés, 46 - Centro, Manaus - AM, 69009-365, Brazil

excerpt: Trees & historical buildings surround this major plaza featuring a grand monument & performances.
detail_description: Largo de São Sebastião, also known as São Sebastião Square, is a major plaza in Manaus that boasts a mix of European and Middle-Eastern architectural styles. The square is surrounded by historical buildings and trees, with a grand monument at its center. It has become a focal point for visitors, offering pavement bars and cafes, as well as hosting live musical and cultural events.
name: Largo de São Sebastião
address: Rua 10 de Julho - Centro, Manaus - AM, 69010-060, Brazil

excerpt: Manaus, on the banks of the Negro River in northwestern Brazil, is the capital of the vast state of Amazonas. It's a major departure point for the surrounding Amazon Rainforest. Just east of the city, the dark Negro River converges with the brown, muddy Solimões River resulting in a striking visual phenomenon called the “Meeting of the Waters.” The combined tributaries form the Amazon River.
detail_description: Manaus, situated on the banks of the Negro River in northwestern Brazil, serves as the capital of Amazonas state and a key gateway to the surrounding Amazon Rainforest. A notable natural wonder near the city is the 'Meeting of the Waters,' where the dark Negro River meets with the muddy Solimões River to form the Amazon River.
name: Manaus
address: State of Amazonas, Brazil

excerpt: Restored 19th-century rubber baron's estate featuring period decor, history exhibits & gardens.
detail_description: Palácio Rio Negro is a beautifully restored 19th-century estate located in the historic center of Manaus. Once the residence of Waldemar Scholz, a prominent German rubber baron, it has served various purposes over the years, including as the Amazonas state capital and a private home. Since 1997, it has been transformed into a cultural center hosting art exhibitions and musical concerts. Visitors can also explore its gardens and learn about its rich history through exhibits.
name: Palácio Rio Negro
address: Av. Sete de Setembro, 1546 - Centro, Manaus - AM, 69005-141, Brazil

excerpt: Forested area with guided tours of native Amazonian flora, fauna & culture, plus a viewing tower.
detail_description: Museu da Amazônia, also known as MUSA, is located within the Adolpho Ducke Forest Reserve, a 100-hectare native forest owned by the National Institute for Amazonia Research. The museum offers guided tours showcasing the diverse flora, fauna, and culture of the Amazon. Visitors can explore outdoor exhibits featuring aquariums, snake and butterfly labs, an orchid house, and displays on native species.
name: Museu da Amazônia - MUSA
address: Av. Margarita, 6305 - Cidade de Deus, Manaus - AM, 69099-415, Brazil

excerpt: 19th-century former police headquarters housing museums of art, numismatics, archaeology & more.
detail_description: Nestled at the intersection of Avenida Sete de Setembro and historic streets, the Palacete Provincial stands as a remarkable 19th-century former police headquarters that now houses an impressive array of five museums. This cultural gem showcases diverse collections ranging from art to numismatics and archaeology, offering visitors a glimpse into the rich heritage of the region.
name: Palacete Provincial
address: Praça Heliodoro Balbi, S/N - Centro, Manaus - AM, 69005-260, Brazil

detail_description: Restaurante Caxiri Manaus is a renowned culinary icon in the heart of Manaus, housed in a beautifully restored mansion with expansive windows overlooking the majestic Teatro Amazonas. Led by acclaimed chef Debora Shornik, known for her expertise in Amazonian cuisine, this establishment offers an elegant yet relaxed dining experience. The menu features gourmet interpretations of traditional Amazon dishes, such as tambaqui river fish, and creatively crafted cocktails infused with local flavors.
name: Restaurante Caxiri Manaus
address: Rua 10 de Julho, 495 - Centro, Manaus - AM, 69010-000, Brazil

detail_description: Restaurante Banzeiro in Manaus offers a unique dining experience with its exotic decor featuring vibrant photos and a canoe symbolizing the movement of boats on the river. The grill uses fire and embers, incorporating ancestral techniques from the northwest Amazon. Classic dishes like fish, shrimp, and meat are elevated with new textures and ingredients that evoke the flavors of the forest. Chef Felipe Schaedler transforms Amazonian bounty into surprising fare, such as crunchy tambaqui ribs.
name: Restaurante Banzeiro Manaus
address: R. Libertador, 102 - Nossa Sra. das Graças, Manaus - AM, 69057-070, Brazil

excerpt: Scenic conservation area featuring forested trails, play equipment, an amphitheater & a library.
detail_description: Parque Municipal do Mindu, established in the late 1980s, was created to protect the natural habitat of the endangered Manaus Sagui-de-Manaus primate species. This lush forested park offers a serene escape from city life, with opportunities for hiking, birdwatching, and connecting with nature. Despite some pollution concerns, it's a great spot for walking and enjoying the calming sounds of the river.
name: Parque Municipal do Mindu
address: R. Domingos José Martins, S/n - Parque Dez de Novembro, Manaus - AM, 69098-257, Brazil

excerpt: Large urban park along a stream, with an iron portico of arches, a trellised walkway & monuments.
detail_description: Parque Senador Jefferson Péres is a well-maintained urban park located in the heart of the city. It features lush greenery, walking and biking tracks, and a casual laid-back ambiance. The park offers a quiet and beautiful setting for morning or afternoon walks, with plenty of benches and exercise equipment available. Despite being close to the busy city center, it provides a relaxing atmosphere away from the noise.
name: Parque Senador Jefferson Péres
address: Av. Lourenço da Silva Braga, 1507 - Centro, Manaus - AM, Brazil

excerpt: Contemporary property offering a restaurant & a piano bar, plus a rooftop pool & a sauna.
detail_description: Nestled within the vibrant Millennium Center Complex, Manaus Hotéis Millennium is a contemporary haven that combines comfort and convenience. This hotel boasts an array of amenities including a rooftop pool with stunning views, a sauna, and a well-equipped fitness center. Guests can enjoy delicious meals at the on-site restaurant or unwind at the piano bar after a day of exploring. The spacious apartments come complete with balconies, air conditioning, kitchen facilities, and satellite TV for your entertainment.
name: Manaus Hotéis Millennium
address: Av. Djalma Batista, 1661 - Chapada, Manaus - AM, 69050-970, Brazil

excerpt: Museum in a neoclassical palace featuring hands-on exhibits tracing the culture & history of Manaus.
detail_description: The Museu da Cidade de Manaus (Paço da Liberdade) is a Brazilian museum located in the heart of Manaus, offering an immersive experience into the rich history and culture of the region. Housed in a neoclassical palace, it features interactive exhibits that trace the diverse backgrounds and traditions of the people of Manaus. Visitors can explore displays on indigenous cultures, art, natural history, and more.
name: Museu da Cidade de Manaus - MUMA (Paço da Liberdade)
address: R. Gabriel Salgado - Centro, Manaus - AM, 69005-340, Brazil

excerpt: Understated hotel in a chic mansion with a restaurant & a bar, plus an outdoor pool & a gym.
detail_description: The Hotel Villa Amazônia is a boutique hotel located in the heart of Manaus, in an elegant mansion from the golden rubber age. Offering luxurious suites with views of a natural pool and indoor garden, as well as delicious cuisine from the Fitz Carraldo bistro, this is one of the best places to stay in Manaus.
name: Hotel Villa Amazônia
address: Rua 10 de Julho, 315 - Centro, Manaus - AM, 69010-060, Brazil

detail_description: Tacacá da Gisela is more than just a typical street stall; it's a permanent fixture in the square across from Teatro Amazonas. The ornate green columns and tiled roof make it stand out. Both locals and tourists frequent this spot for its signature dish, tacaca, a tangy broth that surprises even the most seasoned palates.
name: Tacacá da Gisela
address: R. José Clemente - Centro, Manaus - AM, 69010-070, Brazil

detail_description: Centro Cultural Usina Chaminé is a remarkable destination that beautifully marries innovative architecture with cultural experiences. Originally designed as a sewage treatment plant, this unique venue has been transformed into a sensory museum that invites visitors to engage all five senses. With its commitment to enhancing the visitor experience, Centro Cultural Usina Chaminé stands out as an enchanting place worth exploring.
name: Centro Cultural Usina Chaminé
address: Av. Lourenço da Silva Braga, s/n - Centro, Manaus - AM, 69005-015, Brazil

excerpt: Busy harbor on the Amazon River filled with cargo & cruise ships, colorful vendors & food stalls.
detail_description: The Port of Manaus, situated on the Amazon River, is a bustling harbor filled with cargo and cruise ships, as well as vibrant vendors and food stalls. It is strategically located between Sao Vicente beach and the Adolpho Lisboa Municipal Market, providing convenient access to customs facilities, warehouses, and container ramps. This important port serves the northern region of Brazil, covering almost the entire state of Amazonas along with parts of Roraima and Rondonia.
name: Port of Manaus
address: R. Taqueirinha, 25 - Centro, Manaus - AM, 69005-420, Brazil

excerpt: This remote white-sand beach features swimming, boating & picnic tables with umbrellas.
detail_description: Moon Beach, also known as Praia da Lua, is a remote white-sand beach located 23 miles off the coast of Manaus. It has been elected as the best beach in Manaus by Lonely Planet and is named for its crescent moon shape formed over the Black River. Accessible only by water, it offers swimming, boating, and picnic tables with umbrellas. The sand strip may not exist at low tide but is a sight to behold during high tide.
name: Moon Beach
address: Manaus - State of Amazonas, Brazil

detail_description: Arena da Amazônia, situated in the heart of Manaus, was a key venue for the 2014 World Cup in Brazil. Originally built in 1970, it underwent a transformation to become a modern stadium with sustainable features like rainwater harvesting and solar energy utilization. Despite concerns about its long-term viability due to the local club's modest attendance, the arena can accommodate over 40,000 fans.
name: Arena da Amazônia
address: Av. Constantino Nery, 5001 - Flores, Manaus - AM, 69058-795, Brazil
